major immigration
moves. It would defer
deportation for more

03:57.604 --> 04:04.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
than four million undocumented
immigrants
and permit them to work legally
in the U.S.

04:04.411 --> 04:09.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lower courts have sided with the
26 states
that sued the federal government
over the

04:09.316 --> 04:13.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
program, and those courts have
put the program
on ice for now.

04:13.787 --> 04:18.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the White House said today
the administration
is confident the high court will
rule in its

04:18.992 --> 04:20.827 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
favor.

04:20.861 --> 04:22.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH EARNEST, White House Press
Secretary:
The kinds of executive actions
that the president

04:22.796 --> 04:28.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
took a little over a year ago
now to try to
bring some much-needed reforms
and greater

04:28.101 --> 04:33.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
accountability to our broken
immigration system
were clearly consistent with the
precedent

04:33.340 --> 04:38.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that was established by other
presidents,
and clearly within the confines
of his authority

04:38.545 --> 04:40.313 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as president of the United
States.

04:40.347 --> 04:45.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But that is the
issue that
26 states dispute. Texas is one
of those states,

04:45.852 --> 04:50.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and its attorney general, Ken
Paxton, said
today in a statement -- quote --
"There are

04:50.423 --> 04:56.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
limits to the president's
authority, and those
limits enacted by Congress were
exceeded when

04:56.096 --> 05:01.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the president unilaterally
sought to grant
lawful presence to more than
four million

05:01.801 --> 05:05.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
unauthorized aliens who are in
this country
unlawfully."

05:05.906 --> 05:10.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on the case, we turn to
our regular,
Marcia Coyle of "The National
Law Journal."

05:10.644 --> 05:12.045 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And, Marcia, welcome.

05:12.078 --> 05:13.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE, "The National Law
Journal":
Judy, thank you.

05:13.980 --> 05:17.517 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, some
background first.
This order the president made
has been challenged

05:17.551 --> 05:19.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
almost from the very beginning,
hasn't it?

05:19.152 --> 05:20.987 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: It was.

05:21.021 --> 05:28.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The executive action came in
November of 2014.
Less than a month later, 26
Republican-led

05:28.662 --> 05:30.797 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
states challenged it in federal
district court.

05:30.830 --> 05:32.632 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what was the
basis?

05:32.666 --> 05:38.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: The states are
making a number
of claims here. One, they claim
that the action

05:38.605 --> 05:44.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
violates the take care clause of
the federal
Constitution. That's in Article
2, Section

05:45.011 --> 05:52.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
3 of the Constitution. And it
says the president
must enforce -- I'm sorry --
must faithfully

05:52.052 --> 05:53.887 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
enforce the laws.

05:53.920 --> 06:01.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They also claim that his action
is arbitrary
and capricious, his action
violates the notice

06:01.228 --> 06:07.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and public comment requirement
of the Administrative
Procedure Act. That's a law that
governs how

06:07.234 --> 06:10.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
agencies go about making rules
and regulations.

06:10.203 --> 06:15.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we know the
justices
don't ever, I guess, give a
reason for taking

06:15.609 --> 06:19.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up a case, but why is it thought
that they're
doing this?

06:19.613 --> 06:24.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Well, I think it
was understood
that they probably would take
this case. You

06:24.851 --> 06:32.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have a federal court, a federal
appellate
court blocking a major federal
government

06:32.359 --> 06:34.160 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
program.

06:34.194 --> 06:38.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The top lawyer for the
administration in the
Supreme Court, the solicitor
general of the

06:38.198 --> 06:43.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
United States, went to the
Supreme Court after
the injunction was issued and
said, please

06:43.570 --> 06:47.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
take this case and resolve these
legal questions.

06:47.307 --> 06:50.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think it was a given that
the court
would step into it.

06:50.076 --> 06:55.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, you mentioned
that this
is -- they're looking at the
take care clause,

06:55.115 --> 07:00.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which I read today hasn't -- is
something
the court hasn't done in 70
years. So, this

07:00.320 --> 07:02.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has historic consequences,
presumably.

07:02.656 --> 07:07.394 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: It has potentially
major consequences.

07:07.427 --> 07:14.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The take care clause really will
go to the
relationship between the
executive branch

07:14.167 --> 07:19.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and Congress. So, what the court
says, if
it deals with it, and it doesn't
have to -- even

07:19.706 --> 07:25.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
though it has asked the parties
to address
it, it could rule narrowly or
address the

07:25.178 --> 07:26.913 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
take care clause.

07:26.946 --> 07:32.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But whatever the court says
could affect all
kinds of executive actions that
the White

07:32.452 --> 07:38.792 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
House would take beyond
immigration. So, that's
a potentially very broad
question. Also, there's

07:38.825 --> 07:43.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a very important threshold
issue, and that
is whether Texas even had the
right to sue

07:43.563 --> 07:45.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the United States.

07:45.332 --> 07:51.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Obama administration claims
it didn't
have the kind of concrete injury
this -- that

07:51.504 --> 07:57.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is required for standing to sue.
This action,
the government says, doesn't
require Texas

07:57.377 --> 08:03.049 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to do anything or not do
anything. However,
the lower court said Texas would
have the

08:03.083 --> 08:08.788 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
cost of issuing driver's
license, which is
under Texas law, and that was
the injury to

08:08.822 --> 08:10.557 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Texas.

08:10.590 --> 08:15.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Marcia, it's also
clear from
the reading of this that the
court added the

08:15.061 --> 08:19.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
threshold of constitutionality
to what they're
looking at. What's the
significance of that?

08:19.833 --> 08:26.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: The take care
clause question
was in the lawsuit to begin
with. Texas had

08:26.573 --> 08:28.341 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
raised that.

08:28.375 --> 08:35.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It may be that the justices want
to get all
of the issues out on the table
when they sit

08:35.048 --> 08:40.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
down to finally make a decision.
It may be
that certain justices were
interested in the

08:40.253 --> 08:46.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
take care clause issue. Or it
may be that
certain justices had read a
"Harvard Law Journal"

08:46.526 --> 08:54.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
article by a former clerk and
current presidential
candidate, guess who, who wrote
all about

08:54.434 --> 09:01.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the take care clause and talked
in that article
about the egregious overreaching
by the Obama

09:01.441 --> 09:03.410 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
administration on immigration
and other issues.

09:03.443 --> 09:05.812 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you were
telling me this
is Senator Ted Cruz...

09:05.845 --> 09:07.080 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: That's correct.

09:07.113 --> 09:09.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: ... who has, of
course, a legal
background.

09:09.048 --> 09:12.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: I do think it's
the least -- that's
the least likely reason they
took the case,

09:12.185 --> 09:18.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but since this is becoming a
very political
kind of case, he did write about
it.

09:18.124 --> 09:20.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And presumably
not a coincidence.

09:20.326 --> 09:22.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But on the timing of it, it is
an election
year.

09:23.029 --> 09:24.397 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Yes.

09:24.431 --> 09:26.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What about the
timetable for
the court deciding?

09:26.332 --> 09:30.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: The court will
probably hear
the arguments in April, and
there would probably

09:30.470 --> 09:35.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
