something done. We
wanted our American citizens
home, period.

23:00.045 --> 23:04.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's why we were there. And if
there was
no way to talk about
practicalities of how

23:04.416 --> 23:06.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do that, there was no reason
to have a
discussion.

23:06.819 --> 23:12.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, eventually, really after
the nuclear
agreement came to fruition,
things started

23:12.424 --> 23:14.193 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to accelerate a little bit.

23:14.226 --> 23:16.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Who were these
people you were
dealing with, and are they the
people who

23:17.029 --> 23:22.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the U.S. can do business with in
the future
and get productive things done
with in the

23:22.601 --> 23:23.535 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
future?

23:23.569 --> 23:25.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRETT MCGURK: I mean, we will
have to see.

23:25.371 --> 23:29.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This was so tough. And even in
the last 72
hours, it was literally some
real shouting

23:29.608 --> 23:36.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
matches. And we did this all
bilaterally,
but the Swiss were always there,
and sometimes

23:36.315 --> 23:41.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
