the slowest
pace of growth there in 25
years, all of course

28:21.867 --> 28:26.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with huge implications for the
rest of the
world, the U.S. very much
included.

28:26.104 --> 28:30.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We get perspective from two who
watch this
closely, Ken Lieberthal, a
political scientist

28:30.442 --> 28:34.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with the Brookings Institution,
and Cornell
University economist Eswar
Prasad.

28:34.813 --> 28:35.981 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome back to both of you.

28:36.014 --> 28:37.749 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ken Lieberthal, let me start
with you.

28:37.783 --> 28:42.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How much of a slowdown, downturn
is it? How
do you characterize China's
economy today?

28:42.588 --> 28:44.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KENNETH LIEBERTHAL, Brookings
Institution:
Well, it's a significant
slowdown, but let's

28:44.690 --> 28:47.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
