29:21.627 --> 29:25.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
China has to some extent relied
on exports.
And they're trying to shift
towards a model

29:25.464 --> 29:29.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of growth that is largely driven
by the services
sector, which is much better at
generating

29:29.801 --> 29:33.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
employment. They'd like more
consumption in
the economy, with private
consumption taking

29:33.972 --> 29:35.707 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the lead.

29:35.741 --> 29:40.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they're making very gradual
progress.
Right now, it turns out that in
2015 private

29:40.212 --> 29:44.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
consumption did contribute a
little more than
half of GDP growth. The services
sector now

29:44.816 --> 29:46.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
accounts for more than half of
GDP.

29:46.718 --> 29:51.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this is a big ocean liner.
It's very difficult
to turn around, but they're very
gradually

29:51.623 --> 29:55.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
turning it around in the right
direction.
The problem is that slowing
growth makes it

29:55.827 --> 29:59.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
harder to put in place the
reforms to get
the ship staying on the right
road.

29:59.731 --> 30:06.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The numbers
themselves, though,
first, how accurate are they,
right? Do we

30:06.071 --> 30:09.007 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
