from China on
their GDP?

30:09.041 --> 30:11.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KENNETH LIEBERTHAL: It's very
hard to tell.

30:11.543 --> 30:18.517 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Keep in mind that their
statistical system
was really quite good at
capturing the -- what's

30:18.550 --> 30:23.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
now the old economy, the
industrial economy,
the export economy that Eswar
was just talking

30:23.789 --> 30:30.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about. That economy is not doing
well. They're
now trying to grow, as he
mentioned, the service

30:30.429 --> 30:32.197 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
economy and consumption economy.

30:32.230 --> 30:38.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The statistics are not collected
as effectively
on that part of the economy. So
there's a

30:38.336 --> 30:41.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fudge factor here that, frankly,
makes it
hard to be very precise.

30:41.840 --> 30:44.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So this is the
model that you're
both talking about, this change,
right, from

30:44.910 --> 30:49.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a manufacturing to a more
consumer-oriented,
a service economy.

30:49.081 --> 30:55.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KENNETH LIEBERTHAL: And also
more of an innovative
economy, where they end up not
being the assemblers

30:55.053 --> 31:00.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of high-tech things produced
elsewhere, where
they bolt them together in China
for export

31:00.358 --> 31:01.993 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or domestic consumption.

31:02.027 --> 31:07.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They want to become an
innovative, higher
value-added kind of economy. And
that's a

31:07.099 --> 31:08.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
difficult transition.

31:08.934 --> 31:12.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And would you
agree that part
of that is inevitable, as the
economy becomes

31:12.237 --> 31:16.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- well, as Ken was saying, that
they want
to, in part -- some of this has
to happen,

31:16.108 --> 31:16.641 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
right?

31:16.675 --> 31:18.410 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ESWAR PRASAD: It has to.

31:18.443 --> 31:22.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if it doesn't, there is
going to be a
huge cost on China, because the
model that

31:22.447 --> 31:28.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has been in place so far,
investment-driven,
industrial-led growth, it's led
to a lot of

31:28.653 --> 31:32.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very inefficient investment, and
China is
living with the consequences to
this day.

31:32.891 --> 31:37.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are lots of loans taken by
state-owned
enterprises that are not going
to be paid

31:37.562 --> 31:39.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
back, and somebody is going to
have to pay
the bill.

31:39.498 --> 31:44.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Although this isn't likely to
lead to a financial
crisis, it's still a big bill
for Chinese

31:44.035 --> 31:48.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
citizens. Plus, the
environmental consequences
of this industrial-led growth
have not been

31:48.406 --> 31:51.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
great, and it's not been that
great at generating
employment.

31:51.276 --> 31:56.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in terms of GDP growth, it's
been a great
model, but in terms of the
environmental,

31:56.748 --> 32:01.419 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
human consequences and
consequences in terms
of the benefits for the average
Chinese citizen,

32:01.453 --> 32:03.355 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not so great.

32:03.388 --> 32:05.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Part of those
human consequences,
of course, an aging population
as well, right,

32:05.791 --> 32:07.559 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a work force?

32:07.592 --> 32:12.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KENNETH LIEBERTHAL: Yes. That's
a result in
part of their one-child policy.
And they're

32:12.697 --> 32:18.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really now paying the price for
that, because
they have had a large number of
people entering

32:18.303 --> 32:22.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the work force for years, and a
large number
of working age.

32:22.340 --> 32:27.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now the number of people of
working age in
China is actually beginning to
decline every

32:27.179 --> 32:34.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
year, and it isn't being made up
by kids too
young to work. Rather, they have
an explosion

32:34.820 --> 32:39.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the number of people who are
now retiring
and, you know, getting much
older, and therefore

32:39.324 --> 32:43.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have a lot more demands for
health care and
all kinds of other things that
are going to

32:43.261 --> 32:44.963 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
tax their system.

32:44.996 --> 32:47.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, to the extent
that you
are both saying this is about
managing this

32:47.299 --> 32:52.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
change -- Eswar, you can start
with this -- where
do you see the country, the
government doing

32:52.170 --> 32:53.939 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
well? Where do you see it doing
poorly?

32:53.972 --> 32:57.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ESWAR PRASAD: Over the last
year, there have
been some reforms put in place,
but largely

32:57.876 --> 33:02.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in terms of the financial
system. They started
getting some changes instituted
in the banking

33:02.280 --> 33:04.015 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
system.

33:04.049 --> 33:07.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're trying to make the
currency float
more freely. But the real side
reform, the

33:07.986 --> 33:12.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
reforms to liberalize the
services sector
so it can grow faster, generate
more employment,

33:12.691 --> 33:17.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
take on the burden of growth,
the reform of
the state-owned enterprises, all
of those

33:17.128 --> 33:22.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are real side, supply-side
reform, including
the reforms to increase
innovation, as Ken

33:22.234 --> 33:24.402 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mentioned, those are not going
so fast.

33:24.436 --> 33:28.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if those reforms don't
supplement the
financial sector reforms, this
economy is

33:28.673 --> 33:30.475 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not going to go in the right
direction.

33:30.508 --> 33:33.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What would you
add to that?
And bring in -- and, of course,
we're talking

33:33.245 --> 33:37.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the -- inevitably about
the political
system's impact on the economy,
right?

33:37.282 --> 33:39.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KENNETH LIEBERTHAL: Yes.

33:39.150 --> 33:44.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in China, local levels of
the political
system, you know, province --
most provinces

33:44.956 --> 33:50.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are as big as countries are in
Europe, for
example -- province on down,
really have a

33:50.328 --> 33:56.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
huge role to play in this
system. They have
been generators of the kind of
GDP growth

33:56.201 --> 33:58.236 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that we have seen over the
years.

33:58.270 --> 34:03.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The way this is being approached
now has the
heads of these local political
systems running

34:03.775 --> 34:09.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very scared, unclear what will
be rewarded
and what will be punished,
afraid of being

34:09.414 --> 34:14.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tagged with corruption, not
getting the kinds
of rewards they used to get.

34:14.419 --> 34:20.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the way they're pursuing
this is in
some ways making it very
difficult to implement

34:20.292 --> 34:24.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some of these headline programs
that you see
announced at the top. It's a
kind of hidden

34:24.930 --> 34:29.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
story that, in fact, I think
it's having -- is
slowing down the real economy
reforms quite

34:29.734 --> 34:30.969 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a bit.

34:31.002 --> 34:32.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And, Eswar, we
just have about
30 seconds.

34:32.737 --> 34:35.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have been talking on this
program,
of course, and everywhere,
talking about the

34:35.807 --> 34:41.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
impact of all this on the rest
of the word,
right, markets and all kinds of
things. That

34:41.513 --> 34:43.315 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
will continue.

34:43.348 --> 34:45.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ESWAR PRASAD: There's a lot of
bad news coming
out of China. The stock market
hasn't been

34:45.817 --> 34:49.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
doing well, the currency is
plunging, but
all of this doesn't mean that
the real economy

34:49.754 --> 34:51.790 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is really collapsing or even
stalling.

34:51.823 --> 34:56.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think there is decent momentum
in the underlying
economy. And what we should all
be looking

34:56.328 --> 35:01.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for is not how fast China grows,
but how it
grows. And I think it's slowly
moving in the

35:01.466 --> 35:03.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right direction, but there's a
lot of work
to be done still.

35:03.935 --> 35:06.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A lot of changes
to come that
will impact us.

35:06.237 --> 35:07.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ESWAR PRASAD: Indeed.

35:07.706 --> 35:14.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Eswar Prasad, Ken
Lieberthal,
thank you both very much.

35:14.212 --> 35:17.949 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KENNETH LIEBERTHAL: Thank you.

35:17.983 --> 35:21.753 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ESWAR PRASAD: Thank you.

35:21.786 --> 35:27.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now the first of
two looks
we're taking at the history of
autism.

35:27.292 --> 35:32.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There seems to be more and more
instances
of it, but in this edition of
the "NewsHour"

35:32.764 --> 35:38.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bookshelf, science writer Steve
Silberman
argues that the rise of autism
is not some

35:38.069 --> 35:44.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mysterious byproduct of the
modern world,
but instead a result of our
growing understanding

35:44.075 --> 35:46.711 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of the full range of the
disorder.

35:46.745 --> 35:49.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
William Brangham spoke with him
recently in
New York.

35:49.080 --> 35:54.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The most
recent federal
data shows one in every 68
American children

35:54.519 --> 36:00.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is diagnosed with autism.
Fifteen years ago,
it was one in every 150
children.

36:00.859 --> 36:05.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In his book "NeuroTribes," Steve
Silberman
explores the history behind that
dramatic

36:06.031 --> 36:10.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
increase. "NeuroTribes" has been
lauded as
one of the best scientific books
of the past

36:10.368 --> 36:15.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
year. It won the 2015 Samuel
Johnson Prize
for Non-Fiction and made the
best-of lists

36:15.640 --> 36:19.110 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for over half-a-dozen newspapers
and magazines.

36:19.144 --> 36:23.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Silberman says the genesis of
the book came
more than 15 years ago, after he
wrote this

36:23.114 --> 36:28.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
story for "Wired" magazine about
autistic
kids in Silicon Valley. After it
ran, Silberman

36:28.820 --> 36:32.223 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was swamped with e-mails from
others who were
struggling with the disease.

36:32.257 --> 36:35.727 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
STEVE SILBERMAN, Author,
"NeuroTribes": People
were wrestling with very
profound day-to-day

36:35.760 --> 36:41.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
problems with finding health
care, finding
employment, finding schools for
their kids.

36:41.366 --> 36:47.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, the entire world was
having a conversation
about autism, but it was a
completely different

36:47.572 --> 36:52.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
conversation. It was about
whether or not
vaccines caused autism. And that
dominated

36:52.877 --> 36:57.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
virtually every mention of
autism in the media.
Certainly, if there was an
article about autism

36:57.949 --> 37:03.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that didn't mention vaccines,
the comment
thread on the Internet would be
about vaccines.

37:03.221 --> 37:08.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I started to think that
there was a
disjunction between the problems
that autistic

37:08.259 --> 37:13.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people and their families were
dealing with
every day of their lives and
what the whole

37:13.164 --> 37:14.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
world was talking about.

37:14.999 --> 37:20.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I learned that what happened has
less to do
with the slow and cautious
progress of science

37:20.705 --> 37:23.108 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
than it does with the seductive
power of storytelling.

37:23.141 --> 37:27.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Silberman's
deep dive into
the world of autism took him
back to the very

37:27.479 --> 37:31.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
first researchers who tried to
define and
diagnose the condition.

37:31.316 --> 37:36.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE SILBERMAN: The true
discover of autism
was a guy named Hans Asperger in
Vienna in

37:36.287 --> 37:42.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the mid-1930s, and he and his
colleagues discovered
what we would now call the
autism spectrum.

37:42.994 --> 37:49.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was a very, very broad
condition with many
different manifestations ranging
from kids

37:49.200 --> 37:53.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who couldn't talk at all and
would need help
every day of their lives to one
of his former

37:53.938 --> 37:57.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
patients became an astronomy
professor, actually,
but he was still autistic.

37:57.709 --> 38:02.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And Asperger
saw those people
at this end and at that end, and
said they

38:02.347 --> 38:04.249 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
all share something similar.

38:04.282 --> 38:09.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE SILBERMAN: They all share
a very distinctive
constellation of traits. And he
had no illusions

38:09.387 --> 38:14.092 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about that he would cure them.
He just wanted for them to take
on the challenge

38:14.125 --> 38:17.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of living in a world that wasn't
built for
them.

38:17.362 --> 38:22.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, one of the things about Hans
Asperger
was that he believed that autism
was very,

38:22.233 --> 38:27.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very common, that once you
recognize the distinctive
traits of autism, you would see
them everywhere.

38:27.839 --> 38:32.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Asperger and
his colleagues
documented the range of patients
they classified

38:32.177 --> 38:37.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as having autism, but as Adolf
Hitler came
to power and invaded Austria,
the work ceased

38:37.815 --> 38:40.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and several of Asperger's
colleagues fled
to the United States.

38:40.451 --> 38:44.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE SILBERMAN: They had to
leave. Otherwise,
they would have been sent to a
concentration

38:44.556 --> 38:46.291 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
camp.

38:46.324 --> 38:50.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They were rescued by a guy named
Leo Kanner
in Baltimore. Leo Kanner was one
of the first

38:50.495 --> 38:56.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
child psychiatrists in America.
Kanner framed
autism very, very differently
than Asperger

38:56.134 --> 39:01.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had done. Whereas Asperger saw
that it was
common and a lifelong condition,
Leo Kanner

39:01.539 --> 39:05.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
saw it as a very, very rare form
of childhood
psychosis.

39:05.677 --> 39:11.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was quoted in "TIME" magazine
as saying
that parents caused autism by
being too caught

39:12.016 --> 39:19.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up in their own careers and too
unloving.
And he called them refrigerator
parents, basically.

39:19.357 --> 39:24.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And by blaming parents, that
opened the door
for psychologists to come in and
say, well,

39:24.429 --> 39:26.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
actually, we know what to do
with these children.

39:26.965 --> 39:31.869 align:left position:0%,start line:66.67% size:100%
And the recommended course of
treatment for
autism for most of the 20th
century was
institutionalization.

39:31.903 --> 39:34.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Take the kids
away from
their families?

39:35.006 --> 39:39.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE SILBERMAN: Exactly,
because the families
were considered toxic, in a
sense. And so

39:39.277 --> 39:46.651 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
they were put in mental
institutions, psych
wards, state schools, where they
were subjected

39:46.684 --> 39:48.553 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to very, very brutal treatments.

39:48.586 --> 39:54.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, kids were subjected to
shock treatments,
lobotomies, kept in
straitjackets. They were

39:54.425 --> 39:58.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also put in wards with people
who were not
like them. They were often put
in wards with

39:58.730 --> 40:02.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
adult psychotics. Those children
didn't thrive.

40:02.767 --> 40:08.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Leo Kanner eventually had to
admit that -- A,
that parents didn't cause
autism, which created

40:08.573 --> 40:11.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a terrible nightmare for
families for decades.

40:11.643 --> 40:16.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Sure. I mean,
imagine being
a parent who is obviously, one,
struggling

40:16.080 --> 40:19.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with the difficulty of having a
child struggling
with this condition...

40:19.050 --> 40:20.885 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEVE SILBERMAN: Yes.

40:20.919 --> 40:22.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: ... and then
let alone having
the world think that you were to
blame because

40:22.754 --> 40:23.454 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you were cold-hearted.

40:23.488 --> 40:25.189 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEVE SILBERMAN: Exactly.

40:25.223 --> 40:31.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I spoke to older parents who
had been
told by their psychiatrists to
quietly remove

40:31.162 --> 40:35.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the pictures of their children
from the family
album and never speak of them
again.

40:35.533 --> 40:40.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Silberman
reports that it
wasn't until the early 1980s
that Asperger's

40:40.171 --> 40:42.006 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
contributions were rediscovered.

40:42.040 --> 40:46.844 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That's when a British
psychiatrist named Lorna
Wing, herself the mother of an
autistic child,

40:46.878 --> 40:50.848 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
began taking a census of
autistic kids in
a particular suburb of London.

40:50.882 --> 40:55.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE SILBERMAN: She and a
research assistant
named Judith Gould went to
special schools.

40:55.753 --> 40:59.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They went to clinics. They were
digging through
medical records.

40:59.424 --> 41:05.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what they found was, yes, a
bunch of autistic
kids who met Kanner's strict
criteria, but

41:05.196 --> 41:11.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they found a bunch of other kids
who clearly
had autistic traits, but didn't
quite meet

41:11.169 --> 41:12.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Kanner's criteria for diagnosis.

41:12.737 --> 41:13.971 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The strict
criteria.

41:14.005 --> 41:15.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEVE SILBERMAN: The strict
criteria.

41:15.807 --> 41:20.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, she was like, who are these
kids? Like,
why has no one noticed these
children before?

41:20.845 --> 41:26.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
